## What
Make entity_lookup truly O(1) for both positive and negative paths by maintaining a precomputed entity-to-first-position mapping alongside the MPH. Currently, the positive path (entity found) calls partition_point which is O(log n). The doc comment claims O(1) but the implementation is O(1) negative, O(log n) positive.

## Why
INV-FERR-027 targets P99.99 read latency < 10ms at 100M datoms. At 100M, O(log n) partition_point is ~30 probes × ~5ns = ~150ns — acceptable for Phase 4a but the doc comment is still misleading. More importantly, the bd-wa5p bead postcondition 5 says "entity_lookup(present_eid) returns correct position" — the O(1) claim was architectural intent. Fixing this makes the positive path truly O(1) and the documentation honest.

## Acceptance
1. entity_lookup returns in O(1) for BOTH present and absent entities (no binary search on positive path).
2. New Vec<u32> mapping entity_rank -> first canonical position, built during MPH construction.
3. For present entities: MPH lookup_key_index returns rank, rank indexes into position mapping.
4. For absent entities: MPH contains() returns false in O(1) (unchanged).
5. Memory overhead: 4 bytes per unique entity (acceptable: 400KB at 100K unique entities).
6. Doc comment accurately says O(1) for both paths.
7. All existing tests pass. New proptest verifies position correctness (see bd-jiuu).
8. Zero clippy warnings.

