## Design Decision: Eytzinger with vEB-ready abstraction
Eytzinger (BFS) layout: ~2.5x fewer cache misses than sorted binary search on u32 permutation arrays. ~80% of vEB benefit at 20% code complexity. vEB is a future one-file swap — the perm_layout.rs abstraction ensures zero callers change.

No software prefetch (requires unsafe, #![deny(unsafe_code)]). Layout alone provides the improvement.

## Resolved Type Decisions
1. 1-based indexing: root at index 1, left child = 2*i, right child = 2*i+1. Array size n+1, index 0 = u32::MAX sentinel.
2. Layout is applied INSIDE the OnceLock::get_or_init closure in positional.rs. The stored permutation is Eytzinger-ordered, NOT sorted.
3. perm_aevt()/perm_vaet()/perm_avet() accessors return Eytzinger-ordered &[u32]. This is an INTERNAL representation — callers use layout_search, not direct binary search.
4. For V3 checkpoint serialization (bd-a2vf) which may need sorted permutations: add perm_to_sorted() helper that recovers sorted order via in-order traversal of the BFS array. This is O(n) — same as the layout construction.
5. Applied to AEVT/VAET/AVET permutation arrays only. EAVT uses interpolation search on canonical (bd-u6bq).

## Pseudocode — perm_layout.rs (NEW ~80 lines)

```rust
//! Cache-oblivious permutation layout (INV-FERR-071).
//! Phase 4a: Eytzinger (BFS). Future: vEB swap (change this file only).

use std::cmp::Ordering;
use ferratom::Datom;

/// Rearrange sorted u32 permutation into Eytzinger (BFS) order.
/// Output has n+1 elements: index 0 = u32::MAX sentinel.
/// O(n) time via in-order traversal.
#[must_use]
pub(crate) fn layout_permutation(sorted: &[u32]) -> Vec<u32> {
    let n = sorted.len();
    let mut bfs = vec![u32::MAX; n + 1]; // index 0 = sentinel
    let mut src = 0usize;
    fill_bfs(sorted, &mut bfs, &mut src, 1);
    debug_assert_eq!(src, n, "eytzinger: must consume all {n} elements");
    bfs
}

fn fill_bfs(sorted: &[u32], bfs: &mut [u32], src: &mut usize, node: usize) {
    if node >= bfs.len() { return; }
    fill_bfs(sorted, bfs, src, 2 * node);       // left subtree
    if *src < sorted.len() {
        bfs[node] = sorted[*src];
        *src += 1;
    }
    fill_bfs(sorted, bfs, src, 2 * node + 1);   // right subtree
}

/// Search an Eytzinger-laid-out permutation array.
/// cmp_fn receives a datom at the canonical position and returns Ordering vs search key.
#[must_use]
pub(crate) fn layout_search<'a, F>(
    bfs_perm: &[u32],
    canonical: &'a [Datom],
    cmp_fn: F,
) -> Option<&'a Datom>
where F: Fn(&Datom) -> Ordering {
    let n = bfs_perm.len().saturating_sub(1); // exclude sentinel at index 0
    if n == 0 { return None; }
    let mut node = 1usize;
    while node <= n {
        let pos = bfs_perm[node] as usize;
        match cmp_fn(&canonical[pos]) {
            Ordering::Equal => return Some(&canonical[pos]),
            Ordering::Less => node = 2 * node + 1,  // search right
            Ordering::Greater => node = 2 * node,    // search left
        }
    }
    None
}

/// Recover sorted order from Eytzinger layout via in-order traversal. O(n).
/// Used by V3 checkpoint serialization which needs sorted permutations.
#[must_use]
pub(crate) fn layout_to_sorted(bfs_perm: &[u32]) -> Vec<u32> {
    let n = bfs_perm.len().saturating_sub(1);
    let mut sorted = Vec::with_capacity(n);
    inorder_collect(bfs_perm, &mut sorted, 1);
    sorted
}

fn inorder_collect(bfs: &[u32], out: &mut Vec<u32>, node: usize) {
    if node >= bfs.len() { return; }
    inorder_collect(bfs, out, 2 * node);       // left
    out.push(bfs[node]);
    inorder_collect(bfs, out, 2 * node + 1);   // right
}
```

## Pseudocode — positional.rs integration with OnceLock (bd-vhmc)

```rust
// In the OnceLock::get_or_init closure for each permutation:
// build_permutation produces SORTED Vec<u32>.
// layout_permutation rearranges into Eytzinger (BFS) order.
// The stored value in OnceLock is the Eytzinger-ordered Vec.

pub fn aevt_get(&self, key: &AevtKey) -> Option<&Datom> {
    let perm = self.perm_aevt.get_or_init(|| {
        let sorted = build_permutation(&self.canonical, AevtKey::from_datom);
        crate::perm_layout::layout_permutation(&sorted)
    });
    crate::perm_layout::layout_search(perm, &self.canonical, |d| {
        AevtKey::from_datom(d).cmp(key)
    })
}

// Same pattern for vaet_get, avet_get.

// Public accessors return Eytzinger-ordered arrays:
pub fn perm_aevt(&self) -> &[u32] {
    self.perm_aevt.get_or_init(|| {
        let sorted = build_permutation(&self.canonical, AevtKey::from_datom);
        crate::perm_layout::layout_permutation(&sorted)
    })
}

// For callers needing sorted order (V3 checkpoint):
pub fn perm_aevt_sorted(&self) -> Vec<u32> {
    crate::perm_layout::layout_to_sorted(self.perm_aevt())
}
// Same for perm_vaet_sorted, perm_avet_sorted.
```

