## Zero-Copy Trajectory (Phase 4a → 4b)
Phase 4a mmap (this bead): MmapPayload stores datoms as bincode-serialized WireDatom bytes. promote_to_positional() deserializes ALL datoms — NOT per-datom zero-copy. The mmap benefit is O(1) cold start (mapping syscall) + demand paging (only accessed pages loaded). At 200K: mapping <1ms, promote ~20ms.

Phase 4b value pool (bd-kt98): Datom gains integer Value IDs. The mmap payload stores fixed-size (EntityId, Attribute ID, ValueId, TxId, Op) tuples — true per-datom zero-copy via direct memory indexing. promote_to_positional() becomes a thin ID→value mapping, not full bincode deserialize. ~5ns per datom access.

The mmap module's promote_to_positional() is designed to be REPLACEABLE. When value pool lands, the function changes from "bincode deserialize entire Vec<WireDatom>" to "map integer IDs through the value pool." The MappedStore struct and mmap_cold_start() are unchanged — only the promote path evolves.

This is by design: the mmap infrastructure (file mapping, BLAKE3 verification, demand paging) is permanent. The datom representation evolves from variable-length bincode (Phase 4a) to fixed-size integer tuples (Phase 4b) to wavelet-compressed columns (Phase 4c+). Each evolution changes promote_to_positional(), nothing else.

## Resolved Type Decisions
1. MappedStore is a SEPARATE type, not a StoreRepr variant (different lifetime — holds borrow into mmap)
2. NO transmute for lifetime extension. MappedStore caches epoch/datom_count at construction. archived() re-derives reference from mmap bytes.
3. mmap.rs has 3 unsafe sites (validate_and_cast from bd-erfj, MappedStore::archived, Mmap::map). All documented in module doc.
4. Feature-gated behind #[cfg(feature = "mmap")].
5. rkyv ArchivedVec<u8> access via .as_slice() to get &[u8] for bincode::deserialize.
6. MmapPayload stores datoms_bytes as Vec<u8> (bincode(Vec<WireDatom>)) — ADR-FERR-010 trust boundary.

